# 15. Print Matching Lines

Print lines containing `Support`:

```bash
sed -n '/Support/p' employees.txt
```

This is similar to a simple:

```bash
grep 'Support' employees.txt
```

But `sed` becomes more useful when the matching line also needs editing or another text-processing action.

---

# 16. Print Between Two Patterns

Suppose a log contains:

```text
INFO Application started
START TRANSACTION TXN1001
INFO Payment request received
INFO Calling bank service
ERROR Bank timeout
END TRANSACTION TXN1001
INFO Next request
```

Use:

```bash
sed -n '/START TRANSACTION/,/END TRANSACTION/p' application.log
```

This prints everything from the starting pattern through the ending pattern.

This can be useful when logs contain clear transaction boundaries.

Be careful: repeated or missing boundary patterns can make pattern-range output larger than expected.

