# 39. Regular Expressions with `sed`

Understanding basic regex makes `sed` much more useful.

---

## `^` – Beginning of Line

Replace `ERROR` only when it appears at the beginning:

```bash
sed 's/^ERROR/FAILURE/' application.log
```

---

## `$` – End of Line

Replace `failed` only at the end of a line:

```bash
sed 's/failed$/FAILED/' application.log
```

---

## `.` – Any Single Character

Pattern:

```text
c.t
```

can match:

```text
cat
cot
cut
c9t
```

Example:

```bash
sed 's/c.t/WORD/g' file.txt
```

---

## `*` – Zero or More of the Previous Item

Example:

```bash
sed 's/ab*/X/g' file.txt
```

Remember:

```text
*
```

applies to the previous regex item.

It does not mean "anything" by itself.

---

## Character Classes

Match digits:

```text
[0-9]
```

Example:

```bash
sed 's/[0-9]/X/g' file.txt
```

Input:

```text
TXN123
```

Output:

```text
TXNXXX
```

---

# 40. Replace Groups Using Captured Text

With Extended Regular Expressions:

```bash
echo 'name=Ravi' | sed -E 's/(name=)(.*)/\1Swaroop/'
```

Output:

```text
name=Swaroop
```

Here:

```text
(name=)
→ First captured group

\1
→ Reuse first captured group
```

Another example:

```bash
echo 'Ravi Reddy' | sed -E 's/(Ravi) (Reddy)/\2 \1/'
```

Output:

```text
Reddy Ravi
```

This introduces backreferences.

